               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc>
                        <support>Pre-watermarked early Occidental thick paper, with widely spaced irregular chain-lines. Apart from nos. 9-10, irregular parchment outer and inner sheets of quires.</support>
                        <extent>ff. 138</extent>
                     </supportDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <summary>Byzantine semi-cursive scripts</summary>
                     <handNote>Compilation of four MSS., all written in Byzantine hands: nos. 1-4 by several hands, no. 5 by one hand, no. 7 by <persName>Abraham</persName> (decorated on <locus>fol. 83r</locus>). The erased name in the dated colophon on <locus>fol. 95r</locus> can be clearly read under ultra-violet light: <lang xml:lang="he">אברהם בכ״ר משה קלומיטי</lang> (Abraham bk''r Moses Ḳalumiti). Nos. 9-10 by another, earlier hand, but its beginning (<locus>fol. 99</locus>) and end (<locus>fols. 137r-138r</locus>) were added later, about the time of the rest of the codex.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>

               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate>No.7 is dated 1436. The others, apart from nos. 9-10 are more or less contemporary. Nos. 9-10: early mid-13th cent.</origDate>
                     <origPlace>[Byzantium]</origPlace>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>Edward Pococke's collection of oriental MSS (mostly Armenian, Hebrew and Arabic) was purchased by the Library for £800 in 1692 (see Summary Catalogue, vol. II, p. 1008).</acquisition>
               </history>
